A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justify their policy with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth by affirming that electoral fraud in the US is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republican lawyers in the United States, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the implementation of the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have since 2009 announced new laws which make the registration or urn registration procedure difficult.
According to the November 2010 elections, this phenomenon has gained importance, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identification and proof of US citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare the right to register as voters on the election day, and denounce citizens the right to vote for which a court act is required.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
The Republican authorities tried to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states, which force voters to present a photo identification card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, the US citizens do not have a universal card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million elective persons, do not have a photo identification issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID in 2012.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to obtain the required ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are severely affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with income less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
That's enough.
Students who are regarded as voters, who increasingly vote for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting associations to choose more for the Republican side to use the cards for elections issued by these associations.
No state has requested a proof of citizenship before 2004.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws demanding voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting hispanic votes.
Because it is obvious that two of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 have promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaign for electoral registration in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The number of new voters registered since 2009 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, only 46% of the voters who voted in advance represented the whites, representing 76% of the voters.
Of course, democratic legislators and their adherents have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the veto of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws that require the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of voting rights difficult.
Democratic critics denounce the party political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the decisive states for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have passed these laws constitute 171 of the 270 votes that are required in the Electoral Committee to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
