The Higgs-Boson Analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused some attention last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it's the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "minimum false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not entirely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics conference in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely secure about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of deceiving, and let us look at what it is all about.
In this world there is a necessarily indispensable law, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and try not to be too strong as you will hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to them as well: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantity state", whereby this "state" consists largely of some of its characteristics.
From that point on, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a vicious band of anarchists who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups, according to the website The Particle Adventure by the Berkeley laboratories (which is absolutely amazing), the mesons that we are not dealing with here and the "particles of power" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it has to be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a bison of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
For if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly in this place, in about like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "trails of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disrupted" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the generator must achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be torn by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a range of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) do not have a mass.
For what can all these research be "good", Mrs. Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine in detail all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
Incidentally, there are numerous physicists who most sincerely hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One must say that the latter still has great defects, as it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (against ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Effects
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no such thing.
By the way, in the early 1960s, pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their works would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed himself the first continuous strip laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was regarded as a "laboratory" at the beginning.
Imagine...
Applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has introduced the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can't really know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die... - Le Devoir
With its "Death in Dignity" Committee, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate will have to be resumed shortly, although a draft law will be prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important subject area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him for a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I've made seven years," he said half-heartedly lying in his bed in the house for the palliative care of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it is always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The illness makes her work: an inestimable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to be helped with food.
Courageously, he even smiles and talks to the strangers who are busy around him, bringing him his drugs, and offering him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeping in front of us," says Pierre Brodoor, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to the childhood phase is unacceptable for some people.
"This depends on the ability of the person", he notes, to take a step backwards.
In the opinion of several people working in the palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who care for them are no longer fond of so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But because of the illness, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says before she accepts that you put on a mask that helps her breathe.
Nevertheless, she expects her son to visit her last visit from Italy in the next few days.
In the home Victor-Gadbois you can offer with a group of volunteer body care and help in taking food.
Palliative care is then used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little, considering that one day we're all going to die.
Here, life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
One grants the dying person a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetes patients will no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family and patients alike," says Nathalie Savard's Care Director.
Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years of age who enjoys the last family gathering in the farm and is well supported by his pillows while he is at work, a young man of 36 years old, surrounded by his parents, his wife, and his two young children, dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients less than 45 years old," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who have been admitted to Victor-Gadbois come from their home and 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that should alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the local palliative care company in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
This great inadequacy in Quebec's health care ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of a law on the control of death relief and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been signed by prominent Pallativ care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe in order to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all the right to a high-quality palliative care is given before accepting death assistance.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had a great pain in the emergency room for 14 days without taking measures to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only want to die because they don't get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologens treat their patients bitterly until the last day despite the worst forecasts.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she discontinued severe chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry that I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nurse that it has not allowed this wish after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care in pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the Palliative Care of the Society of Domestic Palliative Care of the Grand Duchy of Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which is aimed at either sporadic or permanent into the patient's death.
We can no longer do as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the possibility to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not eased say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to sleep in me", but "I want my pain to be eased".
