It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange back) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin all net nodes are at the same time depositors of the billing book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can test the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are present throughout the entire network-wide public account account.
The decisive step is to record this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task which is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker who has the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and distinct electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add it a number before the whole thing gets "cracked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other knots can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice (less than 10 minutes) for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred millionths, leaving a certain margin of play...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in computing performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits have been stolen.
"The used vulnerability does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billing book and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November a "mega lock sale" was launched.
"Three thousand dollars were exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the Coinabul company, is pleased to convert Bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat states that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered for the benefit of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB's report provides for a re-evaluation of the various risks that are highly regarded today in the event of a success of this currency.
