A Constitution with the Brechstange in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily granted it the unlimited power, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this House two additional months for the completion of its work.
Egypt has now been based on a preliminary text that has been modified several times for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only provided for an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "stepping right with feet".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to refrain from their intention to explain the text section for section to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of finding his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since the Egyptian people are subjected to an ultimatum with this deterrent vote: " Either you agree with my draft or I retain the unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after adoption of the Constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Declaration of Constitution in mid-November, they have turned their backs on the view that they have not been able to apply their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
Yesterday morning, 11 persons, deputy members, were added to the decision-making capacity.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were generally adopted unanimously.
Incidentally, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, since some members of the board thought that the pendulum of the constitutive assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who only consider this to be a blow of propaganda, reply to "no sanctity".
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have considered Article 220, which confers an advisory role on the University of Al-Azhar, in particular as regards the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "the people who are invited to an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of a theocracy in this."
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"At present there is no concrete religious commitment to be seen.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained partly in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits, "that there may be a ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are rejected by the religious vocabulary.
This refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to how far civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised by the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not presented to Parliament but to a national defence board.
There will also be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as has been demanded by the associations to defend human rights.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy's record is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no longer refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef by Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the ban on torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to comment on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the Head of State will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
AIF calls you the five main reasons for a visit to Israel.
bowing down to the holy places
Visit the Jordan River in which Jesus was baptized.
It means that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, the calming of the storm of the sea and fishing.
Just here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most shrines, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Believers here enter the Passion Path or Cross Path of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here is the Christian view of the Navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where a Christian legend says it grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the walls of lamentation, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, there are people of different denominations left with desires that will then be fulfilled.
Traveling to the Heights
The ruins of the Fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at an altitude of 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins of their own strength.
Everyone else brings a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous Hermon ski area, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly living on the mountaintop.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are nearly 300 museums in this country.
In the case of only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among these is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
Old Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean desert, are kept there as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the Museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers then.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum leaders or souvenir shops there.
Entrance is free, and donations are rejected in principle.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters of history.
The most important department is the monument for the children, which was built in memory of the 1.5 million children destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Star sparkle.
And it sounds the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three main recreation areas of Israel lie on the banks of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
There are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums at each of the three locations.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and therefore even wears non-swimmer seamlessly on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sole) and salinity as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of damaged nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Ancient History
These secrets are located in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city was the famous sea route that linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists enjoy strolling through the narrow streets named after constellations.
Fortuna is said to be the legend of all teams that touch the walls in the alley with their star signs.
In Jaffa you can find newly milled couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusades.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Tonight evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Favourites for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your bad English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is rather not taken in euros, but in dollars that can easily be changed into shekel (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekel).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city to the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground cable car.
A journey within the city costs regardless of the means of transport 6 shifts, which is inclusive of switching for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without sheds and foods containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice of different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, different sauces, fried balls made of powdered beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nigh cats who stroll comfortably and unholy through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to tasty things.
A car rental costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost on average 30 shifts.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists arrived in the Promised Land, corresponding to a 51% increase compared to the same period in 2010, prior to the repeal of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While Members and citizens' rights discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates.
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families who remained in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force, whereby every migrant worker must pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who wish to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail trade.
However, the tests with the time required by the Federal Migration Authority will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
This requires not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of work permits.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the Examining Office will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Popular Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to launch the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the entry into force of the law in the press, citizens' lawyers asked the following question several times: What does it actually do?
What changes does the requirement for language skills have to be demonstrated, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, it is about reducing the number of forced workers that spokespersons of the Migration Authority are denied.
"Many people are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the representative of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelew.
However, their rights must be protected from their departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers to 90%.
Problems arise for migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination.
Zebelew is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him under the pretext of help into a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure dozens of his like months without food and documents and will be pushed 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home you will be promised one, and on arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken off and will not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the administration for labor migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't spit, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian Republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot only control the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but rather the evil: few Turks, Uskens and Tadschiken can only afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school stuff.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizens' rights highlight the important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to be illegal in Russia.
"Welcome to the Heart" or "Prohibit for unauthorizeds"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
Furthermore, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made fast and only for a thousand and a half.
The Russian police staff know that most of our documents are fake and we are not registered, and then cases of blackmail arise.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea", says Tadschike Umed Huschkadamow to journalists.
"Don't spare any costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be faked.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by staff of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for nothing: every migrants who hoped to save themselves the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be bought easily, is that both officials and civil servants agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will get time for a language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where there is no need for active understanding with people.
