Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this space authority at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency ESA. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (according to the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland to outer space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space, not always in understanding.
I remember, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneer work "Entry on Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important champion of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters was named after him on the face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a railway train was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or to brake the Draisin.
The information for this purpose comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-operated shootings.
The research carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that research has been carried out up to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the technical press of the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon was published by Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakeyobomba lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish space company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At the time there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was to be seen that the research of space would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Federation for Space in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in autumn 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been instrumental in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first one started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and didn't weigh a total of 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and 1959 began in the Błędów Desert Flight tests with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further developments were halted.
Following the first rockets of the type RM, the Meteor-1 rocket was developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and its starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport room with a capacity of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B with a capacity of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C with a capacity of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
The accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czechist Vladimir Remek.
