For the US government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the trust of their allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the call of the united states, and the subsequent Fiasco, in the violent attempt to free the hostages, only made everything worse.
The prisoners were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been negotiated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages called out at home a wave of solidarity as well as anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the presidential elections in 1980.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six ambassadors escaped.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring refugees from Iran, helping them to discover their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film venues in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also made Hollywood's cooperation necessary.
In order to make it credible, articles on this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret, and the film is based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Afflecks Film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This will change the mood levels in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no big differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood that come ironically and easily overstretched therefore come.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
From a haunted actor, a respectable director has become, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after Krivi Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without grace (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that the previous films of this director removed from the Hollywood standard.
But Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the emasculation of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and inescapability that occurs when somewhere moves the story.
A similar effect occurs with his team also in fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few he works quite successfully, sometimes helping reality something - which does not always work so elegantly (the scenes in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport is turned off by a telephone call in America, or the pursuit of persecution on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much of action in many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood staff, but their characters would have earned more space, so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thus loses a bit of traction. It is a film that you can follow with a certain interest, thus exploiting the design and the retro style reminiscent of a 70th-year-old thriller.
But it is only hard to arouse enthusiasm.
