Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert in US-European relations, Berlin is balancing it to a narrow degree of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week Germany had initially signalled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin became part of it.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to have a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely changing its foreign policy away from a policy managed by the US, as it were, towards a German foreign policy.
It is difficult to say that Europeans do not have coherent and uniform policies.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still involved in their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as that of France or the United Kingdom.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean specifically from the German point of view?
It shows the willingness to obtain positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are at a certain level different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests had an impact on the attitude in the Middle East conflict and on voting in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, into the Arab countries.
It certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight, either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by including itself in important decisions of the vote, for example in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the US.
That's why I don't think this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
It may even mean that Germany will take a certain amount of respect.
Because it signals that it has to be taken seriously as an international player and its interests.
There are various opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly expressed its support for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the government under Obama probably has quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy at all.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and coherent European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of a broader line and have to push things out of their own position instead.
They're just doing that with the euro.
I believe that Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position in the future.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, already because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they must play a more independent role.
Is Germany itself in the role of an important international player - does Germany even want to play a major role?
Or does Germany still find the lead role difficult?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a greater role, different anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European policy is steadily decreasing, but the EU is not filling at the moment of this vacuum, who else remains?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant to them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly research into the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
