Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically to be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Court initially announced that they would hand it over after the clause, but then explained that it would be published at some point on the Peruvian government website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the Presidential Meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the announcement "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press spokesmen of some of the governments of the Unasur that were present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesperson.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort to hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
The Presidential Office of Peru then sent the media an e-mail with the "declaration" of the summit meeting, but it was the Declaration of Humala and not the official document at the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru was host to the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite the strong appeal of the press, the so-called Declaration of Lima, previously announced, was also not published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but they limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague to settle a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which began on Monday in The Hague, in the process of listening to the pleas of both sides, the Lima against Santiago.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences that we are currently making to this international court," said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, and remains, a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, enters into agreements and subjugates the international courts," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake before the flags of both countries.
The two presidents confirmed that they were subject to the IGH, after Colombia had filed a serious error in bringing an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, in which it was agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, from Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, from Bolivia, Evo Morales, and from Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 following the resignation of President Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Hosting President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The Head of State reads the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set at a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
He said to the decisions taken that the countries of the Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be pursued to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban and organised transnational crime, and measures to improve access to drugs and to the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on a triumphant course, but should serve to expand our production capacity and to show our people a better future", added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read explanation.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvian, located on the cross-axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and of which two should ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country serves for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations", which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasised at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting, that on Saturday he expected a meeting with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to deal respectfully with the maritime conflict following a judgment of the IGH questioned by Bogotá.
"Maybe I'll meet President Daniel Ortega on the morning (Saturday), said Santos.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and also the agreement with Nicaragua makes discussions with Nicaragua necessary," he underlined.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will be as civilized and respectful as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the office of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Minister of Defence of the Block met in advance to adopt the Action Plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of the UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru has the presidency at the time of the regional bloc.
